            <entry xml:id="entry_æmbond" xml:lang="os">
                <form xml:id="form_d5616e66" type="lemma"><orth>æmbond</orth></form>
                <sense xml:id="sense_d5616e69"><sense xml:id="sense_d5616e70"><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                            <q>ограда</q>
                        </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                            <q>fence</q>
                        </abv:tr></sense><sense xml:id="sense_d5616e79"><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                            <q>стена</q>
                        </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                            <q>wall</q>
                        </abv:tr></sense></sense>
                <abv:exampleGrp xml:id="exampleGrp_d5616e89">
                    <abv:example xml:id="example_d5616e91">
                        <quote>æmbondæn alḱī jæ nyllægyl xīzy</quote>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                            <q>через ограду каждый перелезает на низком месте</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                            <q>everyone climbs through the fence in its low place</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                    </abv:example>
                </abv:exampleGrp>
                <etym xml:lang="ru">Возводится к <hi rendition="#rend_italic">*ham-banda-</hi>, сращение префикса <ref type="xr"/>
                    (← <hi rendition="#rend_italic">ham-</hi>) с наст. основой глагола <hi rendition="#rend_italic">band-</hi> ‘вязать’, ‘плести’, который мы
                    находим в oc. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_bæddyn"/> (из <hi rendition="#rend_italic">*bændyn</hi>) ‘вязать’,
                        <ref type="xr" target="#entry_bændæn"/> ‘веревка’, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_nyvændyn"/> ‘мотать (пряжу)’, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_nyvond"/> ‘жертва’. Данные лингвистической палеонтологии и
                    истории материальной культуры показывают, что ‘плетень’ был древнейшим типом
                    ‘изгороди’, ‘стены’ („Маuer“ = „Geflochtenes“: <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Schrader"/><biblScope>II 46</biblScope></bibl>). Поэтому
                    наличие основы <hi rendition="#rend_italic">band-</hi> ‘вязать’, ‘плести’ в названии ‘изгороди’, ‘стены’ в
                    осетинском надо считать естественным. Ср. <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d5616e173" xml:id="mentioned_d5616e124" xml:lang="fa"><lang/>
                        <w>band</w><note type="comment" xml:lang="ru">в значении</note>
                        <gloss><q>плотина</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d5616e183" xml:id="mentioned_d5616e134" xml:lang="yai"><lang/>
                        <w>vant</w>
                        <gloss><q>запруда</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d5616e191" xml:id="mentioned_d5616e142" xml:lang="sog"><lang/>
                        <w>βnd</w>
                        <gloss><q>тюрьма</q></gloss></mentioned>, а для семантики также <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d5616e199" xml:id="mentioned_d5616e150" xml:lang="ru"><lang/>
                        <w>оплот</w></mentioned> от <hi rendition="#rend_italic">плести</hi>.</etym>
                <etym xml:lang="en">Goes back to <hi rendition="#rend_italic">*ham-banda-</hi>, the fusion of the prefix <ref type="xr" target="#entry_æm-"/> (← <hi rendition="#rend_italic">ham-</hi>) with the present tense stem of
                    the verb <hi rendition="#rend_italic">band-</hi> ‘knit’, ‘weave’, which we find in Ossetic <ref type="xr" target="#entry_bæddyn"/> (from <hi rendition="#rend_italic">*bændyn</hi>) ‘knit’, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_bændæn"/> ‘rope’, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_nyvændyn"/>
                    ‘wind (yarn)’, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_nyvond"/> ‘victim. Data from
                    linguistic paleontology and the history of material culture show that ‘fence’
                    was the most ancient type of ‘hedge’, ‘wall’ („Маuer“ = „Geflochtenes“:
                            <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Schrader"/><biblScope>II
                            46</biblScope></bibl>). That is why the presence of the stem <hi rendition="#rend_italic">band-</hi>
                    ‘knit’, ‘weave’ in the name of ‘hedge’ or ‘wall’ must be considered natural in
                    Ossetic. Compare <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d5616e124" xml:id="mentioned_d5616e173" xml:lang="fa"><lang/>
                        <w>band</w><note type="comment" xml:lang="en">in the meaning</note>
                        <gloss><q>dam</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d5616e134" xml:id="mentioned_d5616e183" xml:lang="yai"><lang/>
                        <w>vant</w>
                        <gloss><q>dike</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d5616e142" xml:id="mentioned_d5616e191" xml:lang="sog"><lang/>
                        <w>βnd</w>
                        <gloss><q>prison</q></gloss></mentioned>, and (semantically) also <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d5616e150" xml:id="mentioned_d5616e199" xml:lang="ru"><lang/>
                        <w>oplot</w>
                        <gloss><q>stronghold</q></gloss></mentioned> from <hi rendition="#rend_italic">плести</hi> ‘weave’.</etym>
            </entry>
